===Etymology===
From {{der|en|it|lingua franca||Frankish language}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/ˈlɪŋ.ɡwə ˈfɹæŋ.kə/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|+|lingue franche|linguae francae}} {{qualifier|see usage notes}}

# A common language used by people of diverse backgrounds to communicate with one another, often a basic form of speech with simplified grammar, particularly, one not the [[first language]] of any of its speakers.

====Usage notes====
* The most common plural form in English is {{m|en|lingua francas}}; however, the plural forms {{m|en|lingue franche}} (following the Italian) and {{m|en|linguae francae}} (in the style of Latin) are both fairly common as well. Also attested, but quite rare, and probably nonstandard, is the form {{m|en|linguas franca}} (treating {{m|en||lingua}} alone as the noun and taking {{m|en||franca}} as an adjective; compare {{m|en|attorney general|attorneys general}}, {{m|en|forest primeval|forests primeval}}. Similar to Spanish sentence stucture).

